OL,3,CWhat is a 'flabby high' and what is
OL,4,Cthe truth behind the 'Arctic plunge'?
OL,6,FWhat on earth is a 'flabby high'?
OL,8,FA delightful expression used in the
OL,9,Fforecasting community to describe a
OL,10,Fweak area of high pressure like this
OL,11,Fone tomorrow:
OL,13,FYou'll notice the isobars (lines of
OL,14,Fequal atmospheric pressure) are widely
OL,15,Fspaced and non-uniform - it's not
OL,16,Fdoing much to keep cloud and rain-
OL,17,Fbearing fronts from drifting towards
OL,18,Fus.
OL,20,FA 'flabby high' is the opposite of a
OL,21,F'dominating high' like this one:
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G6/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,317,300,200,140,000,100
PN,31607
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F316A1778054737
OL,3,CWhat is a 'flabby high' and what is
OL,4,Cthe truth behind the 'Arctic plunge'?
OL,6,FYou can see that this one is much more
OL,7,Fstructured and dominant. A pressure
OL,8,Fset up like this is closer to what we
OL,9,Fhave seen over the last couple of
OL,10,Fweeks which gave us the blue skies and
OL,11,Fsunshine. A 'flabby high' tends to
OL,12,Fgive us, dare I say, weather that is
OL,13,Frather dull in every way.
OL,15,FAny chance of some rain?
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G7/9
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
